/*! \page qaxserver-example-simple.html

  \title A simple ActiveQt control (executable)


  The ActiveX control in this example is a layouted QWidget
  with a QSlider, a QLCDNumber and a QLineEdit.
  It provides a signal/slot/property interface to change the
  values of the slider and the line edit, and to get notified
  of any property changes.

  It demonstrates the use of QAxBindable::requestPropertyChange()
  and QAxBindable::propertyChanged(), and the use of the default
  QAxFactory through the QAXFACTORY_DEFAULT macro.

  \quotefile simple/main.cpp

  The Qt implementation of the ActiveX for this example is
  \skipto class QSimpleAX
  \printto #include

  The control is exported using the default QAxFactory
  \skipto QAXFACTORY
  \printto int main

  The implementation of \c main returns an error code when 
  \c QAxFactory::isServer() returns FALSE, otherwise a QApplication
  object is created and the event loop entered.
  \printto }

  To build the example you must first build the \link qaxserver.html
  QAxServer \endlink library. Then run qmake and your make tool in 
  \c examples/simple.

  <hr>

  The \link qaxserver-demo-simple.html demonstration \endlink requires your
  WebBrowser to support ActiveX controls, and scripting to be enabled.

  The simple ActiveX control is embedded using the \c <object> tag.
  \quotefile simple/simple.doc
  \skipto <object ID
  \printuntil </object>

  A simple HTML button is connected to the ActiveQt's about() slot.
  \printuntil </FORM>

  A second ActiveX control - the standard Calendar Control - is instantiated
  \skipto <object ID
  \printuntil </object>

  Events from the ActiveX controls are handled using both Visual Basic Script
  and JavaScript.
  \skipto VBScript
  \printuntil </SCRIPT>
  \printuntil </SCRIPT>
*/
